---
import { Icon } from '@astrojs/starlight/components';
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Section from '../components/Section.astro';
import CodeCard from '../components/CodeCard.astro';
import Progression from '../components/Progression.astro';

const gistSnippet = `gists/                  # pure Python, no framework dependency
  inventory.py         # ERP lookup, sheet write
  notify.py            # Slack / email dispatch

repld                   # imports gists for interactive prototyping
fastapi                 # imports gists for production endpoints
inngest                 # calls gists as durable step functions`;

const gateSnippet = `# auto stages fill themselves; human stages wait
[Auto]   Finding      → system analyzes, writes result
[Human]  Decision     → human reviews, writes action        # ← gate
[Auto]   Execution    → system executes the action
[Auto]   Status       → Pending → Done`;

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/?$/, '/');

const principles = [
	{
		t: 'One function, one job',
		d: 'Each function takes input and returns output. They connect through the data they pass, so you can rearrange them without rewiring a framework.',
	},
	{
		t: 'UI is a view, not the system',
		d: 'Pipeline state lives in plain data. Any UI can read or write it, so you can swap the view without touching the pipeline underneath.',
	},
	{
		t: 'Prototype by hand, then go headless',
		d: 'Start by doing the task manually with Claude. Each repeated action becomes a gist, and each gist becomes a stage you can call.',
	},
	{
		t: 'A human gate is an empty field',
		d: 'A column waiting for input, a DB field left null, a waitForEvent. They are the same idea: the pipeline pauses until a person fills it in.',
	},
	{
		t: 'State is plain data',
		d: 'JSON in, JSON out. A spreadsheet column, a DB column, and a pipeline input are the same thing wearing different clothes.',
	},
	{
		t: "Discover, don't design",
		d: "Do the work by hand first. Pull out a stage only once you've done the same thing three times.",
	},
];

const layers = [
	['Capture', 'Web app, phone camera, manual entry', 'Same, or webhook / API trigger'],
	['AI reasoning', 'Claude Code (human steers)', 'Claude API (prompt hardened)'],
	['Glue', 'repld gist (ad-hoc, stateful)', 'FastAPI / Inngest (durable)'],
	['State / UI', 'Spreadsheet, DB, file dump', 'Same — UI is just a view'],
	['Integration', 'MCP tools (browser, APIs)', 'Same MCP tools, called from code'],
];

const steps = [
	{
		t: 'Interactive',
		d: 'You and Claude work a task in the live workspace. Poke at the browser, hit an API, look at what comes back. No plan yet, just doing the thing.',
	},
	{
		t: 'Scripted',
		d: "You've done it three times and the steps are obvious. Pull them into a gist, a plain Python file repld hot-reloads. Same code, now importable.",
	},
	{
		t: 'Semi-auto',
		d: 'Wire a trigger so it runs on its own: @every, a webhook, or a queue. Add a human gate wherever a call needs judgment.',
	},
	{
		t: 'Production',
		d: 'Event-driven, durable, monitored. The gists from the scripted phase are now production steps. Nothing got thrown away.',
	},
];
---

<BaseLayout
	title="The Playbook — building automations with repld"
	description="How an automation actually gets built with Claude: do the task by hand, pull the steps into a gist, wire a trigger, then run it headless. The same code graduates to production."
	active="playbook"
>
	<!-- ==================== hero ==================== -->
	<section class="hero">
		<p class="tag">how we build</p>
		<h1 class="display">The Playbook</h1>
		<p class="hero-sub">
			How automations get built when you and Claude work side by side. Do the task by hand, watch
			the steps settle, then pull them into code one phase at a time. The same method covers fully
			automatic pipelines, human-in-the-loop processes, and plain data transforms.
		</p>
	</section>

	<!-- ==================== principles ==================== -->
	<Section label="principles">
		<div class="cards-grid">
			{
				principles.map((p) => (
					<div class="card">
						<h3>{p.t}</h3>
						<p>{p.d}</p>
					</div>
				))
			}
		</div>
	</Section>

	<!-- ==================== layers ==================== -->
	<Section label="layers">
		<h2 class="display sm">Same code, different context.</h2>
		<p class="body-text">
			The interactive prototype and the production system share the same layers. The logic stays
			put. What changes is the glue that runs it.
		</p>
		<div class="table-wrap" data-reveal>
			<table>
				<thead>
					<tr><th>Layer</th><th>Interactive</th><th>Production</th></tr>
				</thead>
				<tbody>
					{
						layers.map(([l, i, p]) => (
							<tr>
								<td class="lname">{l}</td>
								<td>{i}</td>
								<td>{p}</td>
							</tr>
						))
					}
				</tbody>
			</table>
		</div>
	</Section>

	<!-- ==================== the gist ==================== -->
	<Section label="portable unit">
		<div class="split">
			<div>
				<h2 class="display sm">One gist, many harnesses.</h2>
				<p class="body-text">
					A gist is a plain Python file: data in, data out. Import it into repld while you
					prototype, into FastAPI to serve it, into Inngest for durable workflows. The file never
					changes, only what runs it.
				</p>
			</div>
			<CodeCard code={gistSnippet} lang="bash" />
		</div>
	</Section>

	<!-- ==================== human gates ==================== -->
	<Section label="human gates">
		<div class="split">
			<div>
				<h2 class="display sm">The pipeline pauses for you.</h2>
				<p class="body-text">
					A human gate is an empty field. Auto stages fill themselves in; human stages wait. The
					field can live anywhere a person can reach it: a spreadsheet cell, a dashboard, a Slack
					message, or a prompt in the workspace.
				</p>
			</div>
			<CodeCard code={gateSnippet} lang="python" />
		</div>
	</Section>

	<!-- ==================== the progression ==================== -->
	<Section label="the progression">
		<h2 class="display sm">Every tool starts as a conversation.</h2>
		<p class="body-text">
			Not every workflow needs every phase. Some jump straight to production. Some stay semi-auto
			for good. Whichever path it takes, each phase reuses what the last one produced.
		</p>
		<div data-reveal>
			<Progression steps={steps} />
		</div>
	</Section>

	<!-- ==================== outro ==================== -->
	<section class="outro" data-anim>
		<blockquote data-reveal>
			This playbook came out of real projects, not a whiteboard. Each one started as manual data
			entry and a few Claude sessions. By the end it was a multi-stage pipeline: OCR, AI enrichment,
			a sync back to the system of record, and human gates where someone had to make the call. All
			of it grew from gists that began as throwaway REPL code.
		</blockquote>
		<div class="back-links" data-reveal>
			<a href={base}><Icon name="left-arrow" size="1em" /> back to repld</a>
			<a href={`${base}production`}
				>graduating to production <Icon name="right-arrow" size="1em" /></a
			>
		</div>
	</section>
</BaseLayout>


<style>
	/* principle cards */
	.cards-grid {
		display: grid;
		grid-template-columns: repeat(3, minmax(0, 1fr));
		gap: 14px;
	}
	.card {
		border: 1px solid var(--color-line);
		background: var(--color-panel);
		border-radius: 10px;
		padding: 24px 22px;
		display: flex;
		flex-direction: column;
		transition:
			border-color 0.2s,
			transform 0.2s;
	}
	.card:hover {
		border-color: var(--accent-glow);
		transform: translateY(-2px);
	}
	.card h3 {
		font-family: var(--font-display);
		font-weight: 700;
		color: var(--color-bright);
		font-size: 15.5px;
		margin-bottom: 10px;
		line-height: 1.4;
	}
	.card p {
		color: var(--color-muted);
		font-size: 13px;
		line-height: 1.7;
		flex: 1;
	}

	@media (max-width: 900px) {
		.cards-grid {
			grid-template-columns: repeat(2, minmax(0, 1fr));
		}
	}
	@media (max-width: 560px) {
		.cards-grid {
			grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 1fr);
		}
	}
</style>
